## ğŸŒ² Complete Directory Tree

### Comprehensive Linux Filesystem Hierarchy:

```
/                                   # Root directory (everything starts here)
â”‚
â”œâ”€â”€ bin -> usr/bin                  # Essential user binaries (symlink)
â”œâ”€â”€ sbin -> usr/sbin                # System binaries (symlink)
â”œâ”€â”€ lib -> usr/lib                  # Shared libraries (symlink)
â”‚
â”œâ”€â”€ boot/                           # Boot loader files
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ vmlinuz                     # Linux kernel
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ initrd.img                  # Initial RAM disk
â”‚   â””â”€â”€ grub/                       # GRUB bootloader config
â”‚
â”œâ”€â”€ dev/                            # Device files
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ sda, sdb, sdc               # Storage devices
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ tty, ttyS0                  # Terminal devices
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ null, zero, random          # Special devices
â”‚   â””â”€â”€ input/                      # Input devices (mouse, keyboard)
â”‚
â”œâ”€â”€ etc/                            # System configuration
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ passwd, shadow, group       # User/group info
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ fstab                       # Filesystem mounts
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ hosts                       # Host name resolution
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ ssh/                        # SSH configuration
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ systemd/                    # Systemd configs
â”‚   â””â”€â”€ network/                    # Network configuration
â”‚
â”œâ”€â”€ home/                           # User home directories
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ john/                       # User 'john'
â”‚   â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ Documents/
â”‚   â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ Downloads/
â”‚   â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ .bashrc                 # User bash config
â”‚   â”‚   â””â”€â”€ .ssh/                   # User SSH keys
â”‚   â””â”€â”€ alice/                      # User 'alice'
â”‚
â”œâ”€â”€ root/                           # Root user home
â”‚   â””â”€â”€ admin_scripts/
â”‚
â”œâ”€â”€ media/                          # Removable media mount points
â”‚   â””â”€â”€ username/
â”‚       â”œâ”€â”€ USB_Drive/
â”‚       â””â”€â”€ SD_Card/
â”‚
â”œâ”€â”€ mnt/                            # Temporary mount points
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ backup/
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ external/
â”‚   â””â”€â”€ network/
â”‚
â”œâ”€â”€ opt/                            # Optional third-party software
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ google/
â”‚   â”‚   â””â”€â”€ chrome/
â”‚   â””â”€â”€ custom-app/
â”‚
â”œâ”€â”€ proc/                           # Process & kernel info (virtual)
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ cpuinfo                     # CPU information
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ meminfo                     # Memory info
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ 1/, 2/, 3/ ...              # Process directories (by PID)
â”‚   â””â”€â”€ sys/                        # Kernel parameters
â”‚
â”œâ”€â”€ run/                            # Runtime data (tmpfs)
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ lock/                       # Lock files
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ user/                       # User runtime data
â”‚   â””â”€â”€ systemd/                    # Systemd runtime
â”‚
â”œâ”€â”€ srv/                            # Service data
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ www/                        # Web server data
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ ftp/                        # FTP server data
â”‚   â””â”€â”€ git/                        # Git repositories
â”‚
â”œâ”€â”€ sys/                            # Hardware & kernel interface (virtual)
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ block/                      # Block devices
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ class/                      # Device classes
â”‚   â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ net/                    # Network devices
â”‚   â”‚   â””â”€â”€ input/                  # Input devices
â”‚   â””â”€â”€ devices/                    # Physical devices
â”‚
â”œâ”€â”€ tmp/                            # Temporary files (cleared on reboot)
â”‚   â””â”€â”€ user-temp-files/
â”‚
â”œâ”€â”€ usr/                            # User programs & data (largest directory)
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ bin/                        # User binaries (commands)
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ sbin/                       # System binaries
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ lib/                        # Libraries for binaries
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ local/                      # Locally installed software
â”‚   â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ bin/
â”‚   â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ lib/
â”‚   â”‚   â””â”€â”€ share/
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ share/                      # Shared data (docs, icons, fonts)
â”‚   â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ doc/                    # Documentation
â”‚   â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ man/                    # Manual pages
â”‚   â”‚   â””â”€â”€ applications/           # Desktop entries
â”‚   â””â”€â”€ src/                        # Source code
â”‚
â”œâ”€â”€ var/                            # Variable data (grows over time)
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ log/                        # Log files
â”‚   â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ syslog                  # System logs
â”‚   â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ auth.log                # Authentication logs
â”‚   â”‚   â””â”€â”€ nginx/                  # Application logs
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ cache/                      # Application cache
â”‚   â”‚   â””â”€â”€ apt/                    # Package cache
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ tmp/                        # Temporary files (preserved on reboot)
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ spool/                      # Spool files (mail, print)
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ lib/                        # State information
â”‚   â”‚   â””â”€â”€ docker/                 # Docker data
â”‚   â””â”€â”€ www/                        # Web server files
â”‚       â””â”€â”€ html/                   # Website files
â”‚
â””â”€â”€ data/                           # Custom mount point (not FHS standard)
    â””â”€â”€ persistent-volumes/         # Container persistent data
```

### Quick Reference Tree:

```
/                           Root of everything
â”œâ”€â”€ /boot                   Boot files
â”œâ”€â”€ /etc                    Configuration files
â”œâ”€â”€ /home                   User directories
â”œâ”€â”€ /root                   Root user home
â”œâ”€â”€ /usr                    User programs (largest)
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ /usr/bin           Commands
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ /usr/lib           Libraries
â”‚   â””â”€â”€ /usr/share         Shared data
â”œâ”€â”€ /var                    Variable data (logs, cache)
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ /var/log           System logs
â”‚   â””â”€â”€ /var/cache         Temporary cache
â”œâ”€â”€ /tmp                    Temporary files
â”œâ”€â”€ /proc                   Process info (virtual)
â”œâ”€â”€ /sys                    Hardware info (virtual)
â”œâ”€â”€ /dev                    Device files
â”œâ”€â”€ /mnt                    Temporary mounts
â”œâ”€â”€ /media                  Removable media
â””â”€â”€ /opt                    Third-party apps
```

---

## ğŸ¯ Why This Structure Matters

Understanding the Linux filesystem hierarchy is crucial for:

### 1. **System Administration**
- **Troubleshooting:** Know where to find logs (`/var/log`), configs (`/etc`), and process info (`/proc`)
- **Backups:** Identify critical directories to backup (`/home`, `/etc`, `/var`)
- **Security:** Understand which directories should have restricted permissions (`/root`, `/etc`)

### 2. **Performance Optimization**
- **Disk Management:** Monitor growing directories (`/var`, `/tmp`, `/home`)
- **Partitioning:** Separate volatile data (`/var`) from static data (`/usr`)
- **Cleanup:** Know safe directories to clean (`/tmp`, `/var/cache`)

### 3. **Development & Deployment**
- **Application Installation:** Choose between `/usr/local`, `/opt`, or system packages
- **Container Configuration:** Map volumes correctly (`/data` for persistent storage)
- **Script Portability:** Use standard paths for cross-distribution compatibility

### 4. **Security & Compliance**
- **Access Control:** Understand default permissions for system directories
- **Audit Trails:** Know where to find authentication logs (`/var/log/auth.log`)
- **Malware Detection:** Recognize unusual files in system directories

### Real-World Scenarios:

| Scenario | Directory Involved | Action |
|----------|-------------------|--------|
| Disk space full | `/var/log`, `/tmp`, `/home` | Check `df -h`, clean old logs |
| Service not starting | `/etc`, `/var/log` | Check config and logs |
| User cannot log in | `/etc/passwd`, `/home` | Verify user account and home directory |
| System won't boot | `/boot`, `/etc/fstab` | Check boot files and mount config |
| Application missing | `/usr/bin`, `/opt` | Verify installation path |
| Performance issues | `/proc`, `/sys` | Check process and hardware info |

### Best Practices:

```bash
# âœ… DO:
- Keep /etc under version control (git)
- Regularly monitor /var disk usage
- Backup /home and /etc directories
- Use /opt for third-party applications
- Mount /home on separate partition

# âŒ DON'T:
- Store user data in /tmp (cleared on reboot)
- Modify /proc or /sys directly without knowledge
- Install software directly in /usr (use package manager)
- Run applications from /tmp (security risk)
- Fill up /var/log (causes system issues)
```

### Directory Usage Summary:

```
Critical (Never Delete):
â”œâ”€â”€ /boot          â†’ System won't boot
â”œâ”€â”€ /etc           â†’ Services won't start
â”œâ”€â”€ /lib, /bin     â†’ Commands won't work
â””â”€â”€ /usr           â†’ Applications break

Safe to Clean:
â”œâ”€â”€ /tmp           â†’ Cleared on reboot anyway
â”œâ”€â”€ /var/cache     â†’ Can be regenerated
â””â”€â”€ /var/log       â†’ Old logs (use logrotate)

Monitor Regularly:
â”œâ”€â”€ /var/log       â†’ Grows with system usage
â”œâ”€â”€ /home          â†’ User data accumulation
â””â”€â”€ /tmp           â†’ Application temp files

Backup Priority:
1. /home           â†’ User data (highest priority)
2. /etc            â†’ System configuration
3. /var/www        â†’ Web application data
4. /opt            â†’ Third-party applications
5. /root           â†’ Root user files
```

